<TEXT>
a mechanical digester is being developed to 
safely dispose of waste water after farm sprayers are flushed to 
rid them of pesticides says the agriculture department 
the departments agricultural research service said wednesday 
that the portable treatment uses ozone gas and soil microorganisms 
to break down unused pesticides before disposal 
cathleen j somich a chemist at the agencys beltsville md 
research facility said the goal is to turn unused pesticides into 
innocuous carbon dioxide instead of converting them into other 
toxic compounds that are disposed of by burning 
we dont want to take the risk of substituting air pollution 
for water pollution she said in an agency report 
cibageigy corp of greensboro nc has entered into a 
cooperative agreement with the agency to continue with the 
development of the procedure and the device to see if it can handle 
larger volumes of pesticide officials said 
the treatment was originated at beltsville somich and agency 
colleagues a year ago tested the original apparatus with seed money 
from cibageigy using it on 150 gallons of typical pesticide 
soup consisting of detergent and water used to clean corn 
herbicides from spray tanks 
within three days the treatment destroyed between 46 percent 
and 96 percent of the chemicals used in the sprayer by subjecting 
them to a digestion process aided by the ozone gas 
somich said that pesticides are resistant to microbial digestion 
but the ozone treatment oxidizes and makes them more biodegradable 
the technology is far from the commercial stage but steve 
dumford cibageigys director of new technology and basic 
research said he envisions the device one day being transported 
from farm to farm for the treatment of pesticides and waste water 
left over from cleaning chemical sprayers 
department officials said the process might also be used by lawn 
care companies 
</TEXT>
