assistant secretary for health robert windom when he rejected a 
proposed project at the national institutes of health in which 
scientists would transplant fetal tissue into patients with 
parkinsons disease 
windom also formed a special advisory committee to study whether 
such federally funded research should continue late last year the 
committee recommended lifting the ban 
the ban does not include fetal tissue from spontaneous abortions 
and does not constrain privately financed research using tissue 
from induced abortions 
scientists believe that research using tissue from aborted 
fetuses could help treat parkinsons disease and other incurable 
conditions the tissue is valued for its unique properties and 
quick growth allowing it to adapt quickly to new environments 
the focus of fetal tissue research so far has been on 
parkinsons disease but experts say it may also be useful in 
treating other neurological degenerative diseases 
nih is supposed to be a partner with science in the private 
area said fletcher who was chief of the bioethics program at 
the clinical center at nih for a decade this is the only area in 
our scientific life that is being systematically suppressed in the 
federal sector 
