foreign nations are getting the message that 
the united states will no longer tolerate the theft of its films 
records books and computer software an administration official 
says 
us trade representative carla a hills said wednesday eight 
nations considered the worst violators of us intellectual 
property rights have improved their copyright protection enough 
that they wont be subject to increased pressure allowed under the 
1988 omnibus trade act 
the act calls for any nation placed on a priority nations 
list to face an accelerated sixmonth investigation 
i am encouraged by the genuine progress made in the protection 
of intellectual property by our trading partners hills said in a 
prepared statement clearly our message has been received 
but the situation will be reviewed in april she added 
us companies have complained they are losing hundreds of 
millions of dollars a year to foreign pirates or to foreign 
government policies that exclude american competitors 
in its 1988 trade law congress directed the trade 
representative to identify nations that violate us copyrights or 
deny access to us intellectual property 
on may 25 hills singled out 25 countries naming eight to a 
priority watch list and saying talks would begin with them 
hills said south korea taiwan and saudi arabia had made enough 
improvement that they were downgraded from the priority watch list 
to simple watch list status 
the other five brazil india mexico peoples republic of 
china and thailand will remain on the priority watch list 
tougher pressure could have been called for if the countries had 
been upgraded to the higher priority nations list 
hills said saudi arabia had agreed to enact a copyright law 
taiwan issued highlevel policy statements moved towards better 
law enforcement and initialed a bilateral copyright agreement and 
south korea had improved policing efforts 
eric smith general counsel for the international intellectual 
property alliance said the group was pleased overall with hills 
decision but that april will provide a litmus test of these 
nations intentions 
he said his group also was concerned that by dropping taiwan 
and korea particularly off the priority watch list its not a 
sign they can lay off their commitment to enforcement 
in both countries they have made some improvements in the 
enforcement area but theyre not there yet smith said 
he said it would be a major advance if saudi arabia enacts a 
copyright law which smith said would be a first for a persian gulf 
nation 
