<TEXT>
officials at three mile islands nuclear 
plant say they will be ready in about a month to begin evaporating 
23 million gallons of slightly radioactive water left from the 
march 1979 accident and cleanup 
a second stage of testing was scheduled to begin this week and 
the water will be pumped into boilers by early december said joe 
kuehn unit 2 site operations director 
he and tmi2 director michael roche briefed reporters wednesday 
to show off the 4 million projects equipment 
this is certainly one of the bigger milestones roche said 
of the expected startup 
two antinuclear groups three mile island alert and the 
susquehanna valley alliance have appealed the nuclear regulatory 
commissions approval of evaporation to an administrative board and 
the 3rd us circuit court of appeals 
tmi unit 2 was damaged on march 28 1979 during the nations 
worst commercial nuclear power plant accident 
water laced with tritium cesium strontium carbon boron and 
sodium will be boiled distilled then reboiled the steam will be 
sent through a thin 100foot high stack and vented into the air 
the 5gallonaminute process will remove all but the tritium a 
radiation monitor attached to the system will automatically block 
releases if excessive radiation levels are detected in water headed 
to the final boiler 
this is not a new technology kuehn said 
he said the treated water being boiled this way is much cleaner 
than water normally subjected to industrial evaporation 
kuehn said the doses from the tritium releases will be no more 
than 12 millirems for someone who would have to stand at the plant 
boundary during the whole evaporation process people usually 
receive about 300 millirems a year from naturally occurring 
radiation 
six additional tritium monitors have been deployed in areas 
around the plant including one in york about 10 miles away he 
said 
he said officials expect the monitors will show levels above 
background radiation but that the average dose for people within 
50 miles of the plant would be 0005 millirem 
he said the amount of tritium in the 23 million gallons of 
water is equivalent to about 18 drops 
solids left from the evaporation will be mixed with water and 
turned into pellets that will be placed in 55gallon drums and 
shipped to a lowlevel nuclear disposal area in hanford wash the 
evaporation will produce one to two drums of solids a day or a 
total of 5000 to 10000 cubic feet 
