<TEXT>
federal savings and loan regulator m danny 
wall says his congressional critics arent giving him a fair chance 
to respond to charges he mishandled the nations largest thrift 
institution failure 
fair play clearly has not been evident much less due 
process he said wednesday in an interview at his office a block 
from the white house 
the house banking committee is investigating the collapse of 
lincoln savings and loan association an irvine calif thrift 
controlled by phoenix ariz millionaire charles h keating jr 
in three hearings the committee has collected reams of 
testimony critical of walls handling of the collapse which is 
expected to cost taxpayers between 15 billion and 2 billion 
making it the nations costliest sampl failure 
committee aides say the panel will hear from wall later this 
month but a firm date hasnt been set and wall said he is 
concerned public opinion will harden and congress may even recess 
until next year before he gets a chance to tell his side of the 
story 
the public sees silence as being an admission of guilt i 
clearly will be eager to respond to every question that is 
asked wall said 
the committee is focusing on why wall as chairman of the 
federal home loan bank board now called the office of thrift 
