<TEXT>
a gay account executive who won a 
weeklong companypaid vacation for two in hawaii has settled a 
discriminatory complaint against his company which would not allow 
him to take his male lover 
this settlement is another important step in the growing 
movement for equal recognition of lesbian and gay couples 
attorney william b rubenstein of the american civil liberties 
unions lesbian and gay rights project said in a statement 
jeffrey donohoe 29 won the trip based on his companys sales 
quota in 1987 the company offered to pay for his wife or female 
friend to accompany him but refused to pay for his male life 
partner with whom he had lived since 1984 
i certainly thought it was very unfair and discriminatory 
said donohoe who filed a complaint with the countys human 
relations commission 
last week donohoes employer agreed to change its policy to 
allow his friend to join him on companypaid vacations and to pay 
donohoe an undisclosed sum of cash gay rights advocates said the 
settlement carries symbolic weight 
the settlement overseen by the montgomery county human 
relations commission prohibits those involved from disclosing the 
name of the company or the amount of money it paid donohoe the 
employer described as a nationwide company avoided a public 
hearing on its apparent violation of the countys 
antidiscrimination law according to the aclu which represented 
donohoe 
rubenstein noted that the settlement followed two other more 
significant victories for gay rights advocates this year 
in july new yorks highest court ruled that a homosexual couple 
must be considered a family for the purposes of new york citys 
rent control law also san francisco passed a law giving unmarried 
heterosexual and gay couples the same housing and hospital 
visitation rights as married partners 
the montgomery county case is not of the same magnitude 
said nan hunter head of the lesbian and gay rights project its 
part of a trend more and more private employers and agencies are 
taking steps and will be forced to take steps to equalize 
benefits 
elizabeth symonds another aclu lawyer involved with the case 
said the settlement only applies to the companys montgomery county 
office 
</TEXT>
