<TEXT>
sid caesar amp company does anybody know what 
im talking about a broadway revue starring the legendary 
television comedian is mostly caesar but not much company 
the show is a collection of hitandmiss sketches that look and 
sound as if they would play better on a 10inch philco than at the 
golden theater which is where the revue opened wednesday night 
the skits uncredited in the program are designed to show off 
caesars unique talent at mime mimicry and general comic lunacy 
occasionally they succeed 
its fun to watch caesar portray a gum machine that evolves into 
a slot machine and eventually is demoted to a towel machine in a 
mens room he also does a pretty fair impersonation of a baby 
complete with whines tantrums coos and burps 
hes dandy at playing a mortally wounded jewish matador in a 
scene reminiscent of his big dying number goodbye in the 
musical little me but there is no overall form to the evening 
at the beginning of the show caesar looking remarkably relaxed 
and fit announces that his favorite type of comedy is rooted in 
truth the truths that follow meander from obvious jokes about 
a mans thoughts as he walks down the aisle on his wedding day to 
an overlong argument between husband and wife mimed to the first 
movement of beethovens fifth symphony 
caesar also resurrects his german professor who spritzes the 
audience with double talk and a variety of accents dialects and 
languages he plays the same love scene in german italian and 
japanese and the results are equally hilarious 
the large supporting cast seven players in all has little to 
do except occupy the stage during caesars brief costume changes 
director martin charnin injects a little fizz into their interludes 
by giving them some peppy but nondescript revue tunes to cover up 
caesars brief absences 
the production designs by neil peter jampolis are meager and 
unnecessary looking as if they were an afterthought added only to 
spruce up the show for its move to broadway after a run of several 
months at a greenwich village nightclub 
caesar has not had much luck on broadway during his long career 
little me was a wonderful show with a terrific score by cy 
coleman and carolyn leigh but it ran only about six months his 
last appearance on broadway was in the flop comedy four on a 
garden in 1971 the man has always been better than his material 
you are better off renting a videotape of ten from your show 
of shows a collection of his best television sketches with 
imogene coca carl reiner and howard morris on broadway the 
mighty caesar is again in a mouse of a show 
in other reviews critics generally praised caesar but rejected 
the shows length and attempt at being a review 
the new york times frank rich said caesar was in fine form but 
there was good reason to worry about his show for it is so 
misconceived that it turns the guest of honor into a beggar at his 
own feast 
leo seligsohn of new york newsday said although the show makes 
for and uneven evening when its good its very very good 
don nelson of the daily news called the show uneven and 
despite a solid supporting cast disappointing the new york 
posts clive barnes was more charitable saying caesar is a 
clowning genius who could have used better material 
</TEXT>
