<TEXT>
states upstream and downstream on the 
droughtlowered missouri river are arguing over how to control the 
precious water flow 
the concerns about dwindling water levels in the rivers six 
reservoirs drew about 80 people from nebraska kansas missouri 
colorado iowa north dakota and south dakota at a us army corps 
of engineers hearing wednesday 
storage in the reservoirs is at its lowest level since the 
system was filled in 1967 
upstream officials urged that the rivers navigation season be 
shortened by two to three months to boost upstream flows hit hard 
by three years of drought but barge operators who operate 
downstream oppose any further shortening of the season 
we cannot continue to operate as if the drought doesnt 
exist said tim edman special assistant to south dakota gov 
george mickelson in calling for a threemonth delay in opening 
navigation we are not opposed to navigation 
the corps shortened the season by three weeks in 1988 and by 
five weeks in 1989 the season begins and ends at different times 
at different ports this year it opened in midapril and ended 
oct 25 in omaha and wednesday at st louis 
edman recommended during the meeting wednesday that navigators 
haul more tonnage during a shorter season in 1987 about 23 
million tons were shipped during a sevenmonth threeweek season 
don huffman of phoenix towing in st louis said the lower river 
levels have forced him to reduce the number of barges he can tow 
and the tonnage of cargo on each barge amounting to a 45 percent 
loss of efficiency 
weve been very drastically affected by this drought this has 
cost us a lot of money he said further season cuts will raise 
shipping costs and hurt the farm economy he added 
the oneday meeting is part of the process the corps uses to 
develop its annual operating plan for the missouri river the plan 
due out in january includes an overview of what happened in 1989 
and how the corps will operate in 1990 
