although president bush and members of congress have harshly 
criticized ortega for canceling the ceasefire they do not appear 
ready to resume military aid to the contras who are reported to be 
reentering nicaragua 
us officials said wednesday up to 1500 contras have crossed 
the border into nicaragua over the past month from base camps in 
honduras bringing the guerrillas troop strength to about 4000 
ortega cited renewed rebel attacks as the reason for suspending 
the ceasefire and hinted he might cancel the national elections 
saying the actions of yankee congress and the yankee president 
will determine whether they take place 
later a nicaraguan official said that country has no plans to 
cancel the elections and ortega insisted in a column published in 
todays new york times that the elections will be held and that the 
sandinistas will win 
bush lashed out at ortega saying the man is so out of step 
with the other democratic countries in this hemisphere and so 
wildly insensitive to the feelings of others that we shouldnt have 
been surprised by his action 
on the other hand i dont think he has unleashed a fullscale 
offensive at this moment bush said in a radio interview with abc 
news hes hedging his bets now 
ortegas announcement that he was calling off the truce reached 
in march 1988 touched off highlevel meetings among administration 
officials and expressions of anger on capitol hill 
ortega is a damned fool and hes always been a damned fool 
said rep david obey dwis chairman of the house appropriations 
subcommittee with jurisdiction over aid to the contras 
house speaker thomas s foley dwash said i cant conceive 
of the house moving now toward providing military assistance 
thats not in the direction of the peace process 
asked about prospects for renewing military aid for the rebels 
white house spokesman fitzwater said wednesday we dont want to 
go that route we want to get free elections 
but some conservative supporters of the contras began discussing 
legislative language that could lead to renewal of military aid to 
the contras if the elections are canceled or delayed 
the administration said bush was consulting with leaders in 
central america to bring diplomatic pressure on ortega to reverse 
course 
ortega wrote in the times it is now clear that there is 
little point in concentrating our peace efforts around the single 
issue of a ceasefire we do not consider it an acceptable 
ceasefire when we cease and the contras fire 
one major irritant to the administration was the seizure at the 
honduran border two weeks ago of a large quantity of weapons the 
sandinistas reportedly had earmarked for leftist rebels in el 
salvador 
officials said secretary of state james a baker iii confronted 
soviet ambassador yuri dubinin with photographs of some of the 
seized equipment including sovietmade ak47 rifles 
under a central american peace plan the contras are supposed to 
be disarmed and demobilized by dec 5 sources said many contras 
decided to return to nicaragua because it would be far easier for 
them to escape demobilization if they were wandering undetected 
inside nicaraguan territory 
at the same time the rebels have asked the us agency for 
international development which administers the current us 
humanitarian aid program for the contras for food packaged in 
smaller more easily portable quantities and for increased amounts 
of cash in nicaraguan currency said an official familiar with the 
aid program 
aid has refused the requests believing that to help the 
reinfiltration effort would be a wrong signal said the 
official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
the administration has asked the rebels to continue to observe 
the cease fire and the contra leadership reaffirmed wednesday from 
their honduran base camps they would do so 
but ortega said the rebels have been escalating attacks against 
civilians recently alejandro bendana a top nicaraguan foreign 
ministry official said wednesday night 44 civilians have been 
killed by contra forces over the past 10 days 
assistant secretary of state bernard aronson who appeared with 
bendana on pbs mcneillehrer news hour said the sandinistas 
never obeyed the ceasefire launching a major offensive against 
the contras a month after signing it he added that 90 contras have 
been victims of summary executions by the sandinistas 
