blackmail of the house 
the vote was the latest development in the continuing debate 
over changing one of lawmakers favorite perks mailings usually 
newsletters addressed to postal patrons throughout their 
states or districts the mailings always rise in an election year 
because they are considered a great advantage to incumbents 
members of each house however have used the mail debate to 
threaten changes in the way the other chamber does its business 
senators dont like the idea that only their rules require 
disclosure of mailing costs by each member the house objects to 
senators use of money from honoraria political action committees 
and party campaign committees for office expenses 
while the house has approved the conference agreement with the 
mass mail reductions the senate debate is continuing it was 
unclear when the senate would decide to either accept the agreement 
or buck the issue back to the house 
in addition to the mass mail reductions the conference 
agreement would establish for the first time separate house and 
senate mail accounts limit the size of newsletters to two sheets 
of paper establish a voluntary procedure for keeping mail costs 
within their budget and strictly enforce a prohibition against 
postal patron mailings 60 days before an election 
the compromise would budget 1002 million for mailings 
including 445 million for the house 239 million for the senate 
and the remainder to pay the postal service for mailings that 
exceeded the fiscal 1989 mail budget 
