a general electric official acknowledged 
thursday that no records exist to prove a serial number mixup 
wasnt responsible for a faulty engine part placed in the united 
airlines dc10 that crashed july 19 
but james tucker general manager of the ge airplane engine 
plant in evendale ohio testified before federal safety 
investigators that company officials are certain that two fan disks 
numbered 00385 were not mixed up 
one of the disks was intended for the scrap heap while the 
other was approved for installation in a dc10 
a fan disk with that serial number broke apart in flight and is 
being blamed for the crash of united flight 232 as it made an 
emergency landing at sioux citys airport the crash killed 112 
people 
the fan disk was made in 1971 a national transportation safety 
board report found a tiny crack that experts say probably existed 
before the crash when ge pulled manufacturing records on the disk 
after the crash it discovered that two disks had mistakenly been 
given the same serial number in 1971 
one of those disks was deemed faulty after testing that year and 
was slated to be scrapped the other disk was sent on through the 
manufacturing process 
tucker said the two disks would have been stored in different 
areas of the ohio plant and were tested three months apart records 
show the part that failed ges testing was sent to another company 
for further testing and the flaw was confirmed tucker said 
but he acknowledged that no records exist to prove the companys 
claim that the two disks with the same serial number were not 
confused tucker said he too believes the two disks were not mixed 
up 
i made an analogy of a person being hit over the head and his 
wallet being stolen tucker testified thursday at the ntsb 
hearing into the crash 
and so somebody comes up to him and said show me what your 
name is and give us proof of who you are he cant do it but then 
they take him down to fingerprint him and then they find out who he 
is 
tucker said the second test that found a flaw in the same spot 
as the earlier test on the faulty disk is the fingerprint of that 
particular disk 
