<DOCNO> AP891102-0214 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the controversy over computerprogrammed trading 
of stocks is compelling investors to review basic assumptions about 
the very definition of a marketplace 
in some ways the search for that definition is clouded by 
details and the fury of the fighting by vested interests defending 
their views and attacking their opponents and by the enormous sums 
of money involved 
away from the immediate fray however random discussions with 
investors and others suggest there still is some agreement on what 
services should be provided by a functional market 
among them it must bring buyer and seller together for the 
transaction of business it must handle trades quickly fairly and 
efficiently and it must establish a reasonable sense of values 
in specific regard to a stock market there seems to be 
agreement that it must raise capital for industry allow investors 
equal access to buying and selling and facilitate their 
participation in corporate ownership while establishing relative 
values providing liquidity and avoiding volatility 
how well americas financial markets are handling such 
obligations is therefore at the heart of the argument over program 
trading which has been accused of causing or exacerbating 
explosive price movements on heavy volume 
in essence the most common form of such trading is socalled 
index arbitrage or shortterm computertriggered buying or 
selling to exploit brief pricing inconsistencies between spot and 
futures markets 
individuals arent likely to be involved because it takes 
millions of dollars to even qualify but for certain brokers and 
pension fund managers millions of dollars are no obstacle to 
playing this game 
among the arguments against it are these it tends to cause or 
exacerbate big price swings it undermines valuations it serves 
little economic purpose it threatens price collapses and it 
drives individuals from the market 
at the extreme some investors view todays marketplace as a 
gathering ground for reckless gameplaying by privileged traders 
and program trading as a device letting large investors skim 
profits without risk or responsibility 
in short they view recent events as a numbers game played by 
intelligent computers rather than individuals investing in values 
something of a chess game in which computers instantly process 
myriad possibilities 
but shouldnt a free market be able to accommodate anything 
tossed at it it might be true in concept but rarely in practice 
markets of all sorts even those in relatively simple bartering 
have rules regulations and limitations 
random informal samplings of opinion suggest that individual 
investors arent totally against program trading most likely 
ordinary people do not automatically fear big dollars or great 
speed as in computer trading 
they recognize that computers are changing life and that to 
resist change might also be to resist opportunity they know life 
evolves in unanticipated ways and ways not easily understood and 
that they must remain current 
among questions now puzzling people however is instability 
for years the nations stock exchanges boasted of their ability to 
maintain generally smooth trading patterns with relatively minor 
price changes between transactions 
now investors are told to expect greater volatility in the 
future than they were accustomed to in the past and they wonder if 
this isnt an admission of market failure or at least of an 
unhealthy situation 
what has happened they ask to the ability to quickly match 
buyer and seller 
why cant the damage be contained without requiring the 
reassurance of government 
why cant the same technology that made program trading possible 
be employed to accommodate or at least reduce the negative impact 
of program trading 
everyone is asking questions and very few people are providing 
answers 
just as an imbalance of buyers and sellers creates marketplace 
volatility it seems that an imbalance of information creates 
questions to be answered 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
