<TEXT>
tiny detectors using offtheshelf 
parts and cheap 9volt batteries can do a better job of spotting 
intruders at military bases than the vietnam warera sensors that 
weigh 140 pounds use 170 batteries 
the miniaturized system using eight seismic detectors the size 
of cigarette packs a portable monitor two infrared detectors and 
a beacon is already being used by the army air force and marine 
corps said dori miller supervisor of the sensor systems division 
at sandia national laboratories 
theyre not the whole answer but they do give you a first 
alert where to look and when to look miller said a 
marine gets tired gets hungry may have to go to the mens room 
and sensors dont do that 
the seismic detectors are buried around a perimeter with only 
their antennas above ground and transmit codes to the handheld 
monitor the infrared detectors can signal a break in an infrared 
beam and the beacon sends a status report on the whole system 
every 10 minutes the system is remotecontrolled 
depending on the setting the seismic units can pick out 
anything from personnel to tanks miller said the system costs 
less than 3000 compared with the 12000 to 15000 for the 
older detectors that were used 
sandia researchers also are working on a magnetic detector and 
one that would be able to detect a warm body she said 
</TEXT>
