<TEXT>
convenience foods popularity shows no sign of 
waning so the trick is to make them better a packaging method 
developed in france shows promise despite some worries about its 
safety 
sousvide french for under vacuum and pronounced 
sooveed promises delicious and nutritious food for just the 
effort of heating water 
sousvide foods are enticing because taste is preserved food 
is spared the extreme cold of freezing and the extreme heat used in 
canning 
fresh raw ingredients are sealed in a plastic pouch and the air 
removed the pouch is then cooked and immediately refrigerated the 
consumer has only to reheat and open the pouch many chefs say they 
cannot taste the difference between freshcooked foods and 
sousvide 
in france it really was quite wonderful especially the fish 
i remember tasting quite marvelous all the aromas are kept inside 
and the moisture said paula wolfert a new york cookbook writer 
but while the process has been successful in europe its 
advantages are also what raise concerns 
the food and drug administration recently warned that sousvide 
foods are fraught with danger because the oxygenfree 
atmosphere provides a breeding ground for bacteria that can cause 
food poisoning freezing and boiling inhibit or kill bacteria and 
refrigerated foods such as dairy products become rancid before they 
become dangerous the fda said 
putrid smell is gods early warning system that food has 
turned rotten said tom schwarz assistant director for program 
development of the fdas food protection branch 
the agency said sousvide cooking can kill microorganisms that 
would provide a smelly warning but leave dangerous bacteria 
unharmed to prevent problems sousvide foods must be kept 
continually refrigerated leaving open the possibility of problems 
during distribution and storage 
it was designed for use in restaurants for people who wanted 
to have sauces ready to go it was not designed for a distribution 
system said theron downs a professor of packaging at michigan 
state university 
sousvide should not be practiced by anyone other than 
registered thermal process establishments where they know there 
are food scientists not just cooks or somebody in the back room of 
a delicatessen 
david shick executive vice president and cofounder of culinary 
brands inc of sausalito calif one of the few us companies 
specializing in sousvide expects it to become common in 
supermarkets a real consumer education has to go on about pouch 
products and the goodness and wholesomeness of pouch products he 
said 
wolfert sees promise in sousvide to feed schoolchildren and the 
poor theres so many things that could be done with sousvide if 
they stop trying to make this gourmet if we would just make 
sousvide of earthy foods cheap foods 
culinary brands ships several dozen dishes with a 21day shelf 
life to restaurants hotels and delicatessens it lets 
restaurants that dont have highpriced chefs serve foods like rack 
of lamb or salmon linguini 
many foods now being processed sousvide are fancy but shick 
said that will change and that his company also makes macaroni and 
cheese and beef stew 
food cooked sousvide should not be allowed to reach a 
temperature higher than 40 degrees downs said one way to ensure 
safety is a time and temperature monitor on packages for a few 
cents a package these devices indicate usually by a change of 
color if the contents have been too warm for too long 
culinary brands uses such monitors on its products 
