<TEXT>
the commissioner of the food and drug 
administration criticized a new american heart association seal 
of approval program as regulation for profit 
frank e young commenting wednesday before an fda public 
hearing on food labeling joined the us agriculture department in 
disapproving of the idea 
the association proposes to issue the seal to companies 
beginning in february for a fee of up to 40000 per product if 
they meet lowsodium lowcholesterol guidelines 
were deeply concerned about a forprofit regulatory 
approach young said 
he said that the determination of what can be put on food labels 
is a government responsibility and that the plan might lead to 
competing and misleading information 
however heart association spokeswoman debra garner said the 
program is not for profit 
the fees ranging from 10000 to 40000 would cover the cost 
of advertising the program distributing brochures in supermarkets 
and product testing she said the fee would depend on the size of 
the company and its market share 
the usda sent the association a letter critical of the program 
as it pertains to meat or poultry which the agriculture department 
oversees the fda has jurisdiction over other food products 
the usda said the labeling would lead consumers to believe that 
foods that dont have the associations seal would be less 
desirable 
ms garner said the plan doesnt need government approval 
the heart association says the program aims to educate consumers 
and help them eat healthier 
