<TEXT>
a former ford motor co employee who allegedly 
received 25 million in kickbacks from suppliers to a ford plant 
in suburban cleveland entered a plea agreement thursday with 
federal prosecutors 
ludwig a schafer 61 of stow ohio is expected to plead 
guilty nov 14 to two counts of mail fraud before us district 
judge julian cook jr in detroit assistant us attorney stephen 
robinson said 
the agreement called for schafer to serve up to five years in 
prison on the first count followed by five years probation on the 
second count robinson said 
schafer also agreed to make a good faith effort to 
compensate ford for the 25 million in kickbacks he allegedly 
received between 1976 and march 1989 while employed as a senior 
materials handling engineer at the automakers walton hills 
stamping plant robinson said 
ludwig allegedly rigged bids from suppliers of racks and other 
items used in shipping and materials handling to ensure that 
contracts would be awarded to companies agreeing to pay him 
kickbacks 
the winning bid was sufficiently inflated to ensure that the 
supplier could pay the kickbacks and still make a profit 
robinson said in several instances schafer agreed with the 
owner or an employee of the supplier paying the kickbacks to share 
the kickbacks with the owner or employee personally 
the two mailfraud counts charged schafer with mailing two ford 
checks totaling 98367 to empire wood products inc of hudson 
ohio empire and other companies accused of paying the kickbacks 
remain under investigation robinson said 
under the plea agreement schafer agreed to transfer certain 
property to ford as part of restitution to the automaker that 
property included his stow residence a 46foot power boat an 
arizona townhouse five acres of land in clarion pa and 1000 
shares of ford stock 
