<TEXT>
share prices closed modestly lower thursday after 
londons confidence was shaken by unconfirmed rumors of an 
insidertrading scandal touching the government and by continued 
declines on wall street 
the financial timesstock exchange 100share index lost 60 
points or 027 percent to close at 21541 roughly midway 
between its session low of 21463 and high of 21603 the key 
index moved around its closing level for much of the afternoon 
although it hit the days highs on a brief flurry of technical 
buying in early afternoon trading 
volume was 3484 million shares down from 3799 million on 
wednesday 
the widely circulated insidertrading rumor was tied to a report 
in a scottish newspaper that a british television network was about 
to name at least one senior government official in a report on 
insider dealing the rumor prompted speculation of further 
upheavals within the government and sent london shares lower at the 
outset 
the specific focus was on transport minister cecil parkinson 
who strongly denied the rumors 
the denial helped ease the markets worries but dealers said 
more wind was taken out of londons sails by a subsequent 
announcement that ford motor co reached an agreed bid of 850 pence 
a share or 16 billion pounds for british automaker jaguar plc 
the news along with a statement from general motors corp 
ended most of the speculation over a bidding war for the luxury 
automaker 
wall streets early declines kept london under pressure for much 
of the afternoon dealers said 
the insidertrading rumors really kept the market at bay a 
senior dealer with kleinwort benson securities said it set the 
tone but mostly people were just not too keen to rush and buy it 
and they werent too keen to sell it either 
the big stock feature of the day however was jaguar at 30 
million shares traded 
the ft 30share index settled 68 points lower at 17313 the 
ft 500share index was down 372 at 119509 
