<DOCNO> AP891102-0284 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
increases in the prices farmers get for their 
crops and livestock have not kept up with the cost of producing 
them agriculture department figures show 
since 1977 prices paid by farmers for things they need to 
produce crops and livestock have risen 78 percent prices received 
by farmers for those crops and livestock meanwhile have gone up 
44 percent 
it doesnt take much expertise in economics to assert that 
something is out of whack and that the marketplace has 
shortchanged farmers by not keeping pace with rising expenses 
that is one reason congress has provided subsidies for farmers to 
help make up the difference 
last weeks agricultural prices report by the departments 
national agricultural statistics service included some comparative 
figures to show how the expenses of farming have changed in the 
last year 
prices are not the same as expenditures and do not necessarily 
translate into a financial balance sheet for the nations farmers 
for example not every farmer will buy a tractor this year 
which costs more than it did last year same for hay balers 
shovels fencing and other equipment used on the farm 
moreover all farmers do not buy the same things a vegetable 
farmer in california might be upset by a price increase for cartons 
used for produce but an iowa hog producer would be more interested 
in feed prices 
but if prices of several items keep going up over a long period 
of time it has an impact energy costs for example are almost 
universally important regardless of a farms location or 
specialty so are interest rates 
and if prices paid for crops and livestock remain the same or 
decline there will be trouble at the bank when the loan comes due 
not all purchase items are surveyed by usda every month but the 
report for october included several categories that are looked at 
once or twice a year 
the overall price index of prices paid for commodities and 
services interest taxes and farm wage rates was reported at 178 
in october compared to a rating of 100 for 1977 which is used by 
the usda as the base year for comparisons 
the index just for items used by farmers for production stood at 
164 in october these include prices for feeder livestock feed 
gasoline building and fencing materials machinery fertilizer 
trucks and other products 
one of the quirks in the price index is that some basic items 
are an expense for farmers who buy them and income for others who 
produce and sell the commodity corn and other feed grains are 
examples along with feeder cattle and feeder pigs 
feed prices in october had an index reading of 128 the report 
said that was a 38 percent drop from july and was 92 percent 
below october 1988 prices of feeder livestock were down 16 
percent from july but were unchanged from a year ago 
the feeder livestock price index was 196 in october nearly 
double what it was in the 1977 base year 
the index for fertilizer was 131 in october down 71 percent 
from the previous reading taken in april and 22 percent below a 
year ago 
in the category of fuels and energy the index stood at 184 in 
october down 21 percent from july but 115 percent above october 
1988 
for bigticket items the index tracking tractors and 
selfpropelled machinery rose 36 percent from last april to 199 in 
october about double the 1977 price average it was also a 59 
percent increase from a year earlier 
a big fourwheeldrive tractor in the 170to 240horsepower 
range cost an average of 79500 in october according to the 
survey down 200 from april but up 2700 from last year 
twowheeldrive tractors in the range of 110 to 129 horsepower 
were reported at 44600 last month up from 43200 in april and 
41200 a year ago 
a large capacity selfpropelled combine with grain head was 
shown at 99800 against 91600 in october 1988 
there are plenty of smaller lessglamorous items that are 
necessary in farming and many of these have to be replaced or 
added to from time to time here are a few of those price 
comparisons 
rough boards for farm fences and construction 523 per 1000 
board feet in october up from 521 in july and 511 a year ago 
house paint exterior latex 1660 per gallon compared with 
1650 in july and 1610 a year ago 
baler twine 2210 per 40pound bale up from 2180 in april 
and 2120 a year ago 
electric drill threeeighths inch variable speed reversible 
4830 in october and 4660 a year earlier 
pail 12quart metal heavy galvanized 605 compared with 
578 both in april and a year ago 
rear tractor tire 18438 sixply 437 in october 428 in 
april and 425 a year ago 
</TEXT>
