<TEXT>
president bush on thursday commended two 
companies xerox corp and the milliken amp co textile company as 
examples of firms that are leading the resurgence in american 
business leadership 
bush presented the 1989 malcolm baldrige national quality award 
named for the late commerce secretary to the chairmen of the two 
companies in a ceremony at the commerce department 
bush said the two companies responded to the need for 
improvement in quality and service by us companies which are 
national priorities as never before 
in recent years americans have felt the sting of fierce 
competition on a global scale and weve learned to see foreign 
competition not as an excuse to close doors and raise barriers but 
as an incentive to renew our own commitment to excellence 
the president lauded both xerox and milliken for creative 
management practices 
theyre leading the resurgence in american business 
leadership he said most companies catch hell from the 
competition but these two companies are in the lead because no 
competitor gave them a tougher time than they gave themselves 
bush said there was a time when both xerox and milliken were 
being steadily squeezed out by the intense foreign and domestic 
competition in the midst of this crisis the men and women of 
these companies found within themselves the will to make a 
painstaking reassessment and the drive to win back that market 
share 
xerox the stamford connbased copyproducts giant employs 
50200 people throughout the country and makes more than 250 kinds 
of documentprocessing equipment its 1988 us sales topped 6 
billion 
the privately owned milliken headquartered in spartanburg 
sc has 28 businesses that produce textile and chemical products 
with annual sales of more than 1 billion 
millikens 14300 employees are called associates of the 
company whose management structure relies heavily on teams such as 
the corrective active teams formed to address manufacturing and 
business problems and supplier action teams that deal with the 
firms relationships with its suppliers 
the malcolm baldrige award honors the memory of the commerce 
secretary and rodeo enthusiast who was killed in a freak accident 
in july 1987 he was crushed by a horse that fell on him while he 
was cattle roping 
